==English==
===Etymology===
Middle English ''nether, nethere, nithere'' < Old English ''nithera,'' < ''nither, nithor,'' adverb, down, downward; akin to [[Old Saxon]] ''nithiri,'' adjective, nether, nithar, adverb, down, [[Old High German]] ''nidari, nidaro,'' adjective, nether, ''nidar,'' adverb, down, [[Old Norse]] ''nethri, netharri,'' adjective, nether, ''nithr,'' adverb, down; all from a Germanic word that is a compar. of a word akin to [[Sanskrit]] ''ni'' down; akin to Old English ''in'' -- more at IN
===Adjective===
#lower; under <The disappointed child’s ''nether'' lip quivered.>
#lying or conceived as lying beneath the earth’s surface: <the ''nether'' regions>